The '''Brazilian Gay, Lesbian, Bisexual, Travesti, Transsexual and Intersex Association''' ('''Associação Brasileira de Gays, Lésbicas, Bissexuais, Travestis, Transexuais e Intersexos''' or '''ABGLT'''), is a national network made up of 203 member groups, including about 141 gay, lesbian, and trans groups, and about 62 "collaborating" organizations which are involved with human rights and AIDS. Since July 2009, ABGLT has consultative status with the [[United Nations Economic and Social Council]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://old.ilga.org/news_results.asp?LanguageID=1&FileID=1070&ZoneID=5&FileCategory=44 |title=ILGA &#124; UN Committee on NGOs postpones decision on the status of ABGLT until January 2008 |publisher=ILGA |date=2007-05-22 |accessdate=May 9, 2010 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100713184014/http://old.ilga.org/news_results.asp?LanguageID=1&FileCategory=44&ZoneID=5&FileID=1070 |archive-date=2010-07-13 |dead-url=yes |df= }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://old.ilga.org/news_results.asp?FileCategory=44&ZoneID=7&FileID=1274 |title=ILGA &#124; First Lesbian, Gay, Bisexual, and Transgender Organization from the Global South to Gain Consultative Status |publisher=ILGA |date= |accessdate=2010-05-09 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100713163202/http://old.ilga.org/news_results.asp?FileCategory=44&ZoneID=7&FileID=1274 |archive-date=2010-07-13 |dead-url=yes |df= }}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://gonline.uol.com.br/site/arquivos/estatico/gnews/gnews_noticia_22625.htm |title=ONU concede status consultivo a ABGLT |publisher=G Online |date=2009-07-27 |language=Portuguese |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090802002528/http://gonline.uol.com.br/site/arquivos/estatico/gnews/gnews_noticia_22625.htm |archivedate=2009-08-02 |df= }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://daccessdds.un.org/doc/UNDOC/GEN/N09/255/98/PDF/N0925598.pdf?OpenElement |title=Economic and Social Council: Report of the Committee on Non-Governmental Organizations on its 2009 regular session }}{{dead link|date=October 2016 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.c-fam.org/publications/id.1010/pub_detail.asp |title=NGO Committee Rejects Brazilian Homosexual Group for UN Accreditation |publisher=Catholic Family & Human Rights Institute, International Organizations Research Group |date=February 12, 2009 |accessdate=May 9, 2010 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090707081522/http://www.c-fam.org/publications/id.1010/pub_detail.asp |archivedate=July 7, 2009 |df= }}</ref>
It was established by 31 founding groups on January 31, 1995. The organization claims to be the largest LGBT network in [[Latin America]].
== Objectives == According to ABGLT's mission statement, the organization aims "to promote actions that guarantee the citizenship and human rights of lesbians, gays, bisexuals, transvestites and transsexuals, contributing to the construction of a democratic society in which no person is subjected to any form of discrimination, coercion or violence, because of their sexual orientation and gender identity.”
Currently, ABGLT’s objectives include:<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://abgltbrasil.blogspot.ie/p/pagina-em-construcao.html|title=A ABGLT|website=abgltbrasil.blogspot.ie|access-date=2018-02-07}}</ref> * Monitoring the Brazil Without Homophobia Program * Combatting homophobia in schools * Combating [[HIV/AIDS|AIDS]] and other sexually-transmitted diseases * The recognition of sexual orientation and gender identity as human rights within [[Mercosur]] * Advocating for LGBT-friendly government policies and budgets * Training lesbian leaders in human rights and advocacy * The promotion of employment and welfare opportunities for transgender individuals; * Training legal consultants on LGBT citizenship issues
