{{for|the Mexican consortium of universities|CUMEX}} {{Infobox event | image = The CumEx-files.png | image_size = 300px | caption = | time = | duration = | date = {{start date|2018|10|18}}<ref name="cumex"/> | venue = | location = [[Europe]] | coordinates = <!-- {{coord|LAT|LON|region:XXXX_type:event|display=inline,title}} --> | also_known_as = | type = [[Tax evasion]] | theme = | cause = | motive = | outcome = Loss of roughly $63.2 billion.<ref name="cumex"/> | target = | first_reporter = | website = {{url|https://cumex-files.com/en/}} }} [[File:CumEx-Files - Countries affected by the fraud.png|thumb|upright=1.3|Countries affected by the fraud]] The '''CumEx-Files''' is a [[tax fraud]] scheme discovered in 2017 by a collaboration between a number of European news media outlets.<ref name="cumex">{{cite web|url=https://www.dacbeachcroft.com/es/articles/2017/february/cum-ex-trading-scandal-in-germany-a-huge-challenge-for-financial-institutions-and-the-insurance-industry|title=Cum-Ex trading scandal in Germany – A huge challenge for financial institutions and the insurance industry}}</ref> A network of banks, stock traders and top lawyers has obtained billions from the European treasuries through suspected [[fraud]] and speculation with [[dividend tax]]. The five hardest hit countries may have lost at least $62.9 billion.<ref name="dk">{{cite web |url=https://www.dr.dk/nyheder/penge/tema/skattesvindel|title=Skattesvindel|date=18 October 2018|access-date=18 October 2018 |language=Danish|trans-title=tax fraud}}</ref> [[Germany]] is the hardest hit country, with around $36.2 billion withdrawn from the German treasury.<ref name="no">{{cite web |url=https://www.nrk.no/urix/norge-rammet-av-europeisk-skatteskandale-1.14253588|title=Norge rammet av europeisk skatteskandale|last=Vartdal |first=Ragnhild |date=18 October 2018|access-date=18 October 2018 |language=Norwegian|trans-title=Norway hit by European tax scandal}}</ref> Estimated losses for other countries include at least €17 billion for France, €4.5 billion in Italy, €1.7 billion in Denmark and €201 million for Belgium.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.lepoint.fr/economie/cumex-files-la-fraude-fiscale-a-55-milliards-d-euros-18-10-2018-2263950_28.php|title=« CumEx Files » : la fraude fiscale à 55 milliards d'euros|date=18 October 2018|access-date=20 October 2018 |language=French|trans-title="CumEx Files": tax fraud for 55 billion euros}}</ref>
== Method == The network stole several billion Euros from the treasury, through what [[Correctiv]] calls a "cum-ex" trade:
The participants in the network would lend each other shares in large companies, so that to tax authorities there would appear to be two owners of the shares, when in reality there was only one. The bank that was used in stock trading would then issue a "confirmation" to the investor that tax on the dividend payment had been paid - without it actually being done. "It’s a bit like parents claiming a child benefit for two – or more – children when there is only one child in the family." writes Correctiv.<ref name="cumex"/> This practice was outlawed in 2012.<ref name=BBC>{{Cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-europe-40199259 |title=Germany fears huge losses in massive tax scandal |last=Hill |first=Jenny |date=2017-06-09 |website=BBC News |access-date=2018-10-29}}</ref>
The name "cum-ex" is derived from Latin, meaning "with without", and refers to the disappearing nature of the fraudulent dividend payments.<ref> {{cite web |url=https://www.accountingtoday.com/articles/banco-santander-joins-list-of-banks-in-german-cum-ex-tax-dodge-crackdown|title=Santander joins list of banks in German tax-dodge crackdown|last=Matussek |first=Karin |date=18 October 2018|access-date=20 October 2018 |language=English}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.lemonde.fr/cumex-files/video/2018/10/18/cumex-files-comment-arnaquer-le-fisc-avec-la-bourse_5371091_5369767.html|title=CumEx Files : comment des actionnaires utilisent la Bourse pour arnaquer le fisc|date=18 October 2018|access-date=20 October 2018 |language=French|trans-title=CumEx Files: How shareholders use the Stock Exchange to scam tax}}</ref>
== Discovery == State Commissioner August Schäfer first warned of the practice in 1992, after the testimony of five whistleblowers. However, they remained widespread until an administrative assistant in the central German tax office noticed abnormally large tax rebate claims from a US pension fund.<ref name="BBC" />
